  "passageParts": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "In our contemporary culture,the prospect of communicating with- or even looking at-a stranger is virtually unbearable. Everyone around us seems to agree by the way they fiddle with their phones,even without a\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 1
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nunderground.\n It's a sad reality - our desire to avoid interacting with other human beings - because there's\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 2
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto be gained from talking to the stranger standing by you. But you wouldn't know it,\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 3
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\ninto your phone.This universal armor sends the\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 4
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​:\"Please don't approach me.\"\n What is it that makes us feel we need to hide\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 5
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nour screens?\n One answer is fear,according to Jon Wortmann, executive mental coach. We fear rejection, or that our innocent social advances will be\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 6
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nas \"creepy,\".We fear we'11 be\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 7
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​.We fear we'11 be disruptive. Strangers are inherently\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 8
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto us, so we are more likely to feel\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 9
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nwhen communicating with them compared with our friends and acquaintances.To avoid this anxiety, we\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 10
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto our phones. \"Phones become our security blanket,\"Wortmann says.\"They are our happy glasses that protect us from what we perceive is going to be more\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 11
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​.\"\n But once we rip off the bandaid, tuck our smartphones in our pockets and look up, it doesn't\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 12
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nso bad.In one 2011 experiment,behavioral scientists Nicholas Epley and Juliana Schroeder asked commuters to do the unthinkable: Start a\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 13
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​.They had Chicago train commuters talk to their fellow\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 14
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​.\"When Dr.Epley and Ms. Schroeder asked other people in the same train station to\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 15
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nhow they would feel after talking to a stranger,the commuters thought their\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 16
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nwould be more pleasant if they sat on their own,\" the New York Times summarizes. Though the participants didn't expect a positive experience,after they\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nwith the experiment,\"not a single person reported having been snubbed.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": ", these commutes were reportedly more enjoyable compared with those without communication, which makes absolute sense, "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " human beings thrive off of social connections. It's that "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": ": Talking to strangers can make you feel connected."
    }
  ],
